===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|then|then(ne)|lang=enm}}, {{term|than|than(ne)|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|þonne|lang=ang}}, {{term|þanne|lang=ang}}, {{term|þænne||then, at that time|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|þan-||þana-|at that (time), then|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Germanic|þa-|demonstrative pronoun|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|to-|demonstrative pronoun|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|dan||then|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|dann||then|lang=de}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|þá||then|lang=is}}. Related to {{l|en|than}}.

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{context|temporal location}} at that [[time]]
#: ''He was happy '''then'''.''
# {{context|temporal location}} soon afterward.
#: ''He fixed it, '''then''' left.''
# {{context|sequence}} next in order; in addition.
#: ''There are three green ones, '''then''' a blue one.''
# {{context|conjunctive}} in that case.
#: ''If it’s locked, '''then''' we’ll need the key.''
#: ''You don't like potatoes? What do you want me to cook, '''then'''?''
# {{context|sequence}} at the same time; on the other hand.
#: ''That’s a nice shirt, but '''then''', so is the other one.''
# {{obsolete}} At the time that; [[when]].
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book I.23:
#*: '''Than''' the knyght sawe hym lye soo on the ground, he alyght and was passynge heuy, for he wende he had slayne hym [...].

